We are pleased to announce that our instrument control software teams are actively investing in Good Laboratory Practice (GLP) and broader GxP‑related features across timsControl, flexControl, and tqControl. Initial GLP feature sets will become available after ASMS 2026, with a clearly defined, multi‑year roadmap extending through 2027 and 2028. 

This initiative reflects the growing importance of data integrity, traceability, and controlled operations for our customers—particularly in pharmaceutical and regulated environments—and underlines our long‑term commitment to supporting compliance‑driven workflows. 

Why GLP Is Becoming Increasingly Important 

Regulatory expectations around data integrity, controlled access, and traceability continue to rise, especially for customers in Pharma, BioPharma, and CROs. These customers increasingly require software capabilities that help them 

enforce user‑based access control, 

ensure traceable and trustworthy data handling, and 

support internal validation and audit readiness. 

While compliance always remains the responsibility of the customer, GLP‑oriented software functionality is now a key purchasing and qualification criterion for regulated laboratories and is becoming critical even in early‑stage and translational research environments. 

 

 

 

